Music Genre Prediction and Multiclass Classification¶

By Chibueze Nwade & Joshua Ng

Brief¶

The goal of this tutorial is to compare Machine Learning models to predict the genre of popular songs and to determine how each model fairs in handling a Multiclass Classification problem with significant class imbalances. The models used in this tutorial are the Logistic Regression model, K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier, Decision Tree Classifier, and Random Forest Classifier.

Introduction¶

It is very common to listen to a song and wonder who is the artist that made the song or what the name of the song is. This has ultimately resulted in various forms of applications being created such as Shazam, the song identification feature of Google Assistant, and many others. Have you, however, ever wondered what a song’s genre is from listening to it.

If you have, then you are in luck because that is the purpose of this tutorial. In this tutorial, we are going to demonstrate the process taken to create a Machine Learning model (or better yet, a variety of Machine Learning models) that predicts the genre of a song based on its features such as the artist that made the song, the energy in the song, the tempo of the song (labeled as beats per minute), and much more. To accomplish this, we are going to use the Spotify – All Time Top 2000s Mega Dataset that we found on Kaggle, that provides information on the most popular songs from the year 1956 to the year 2019.

In addition to showcasing the process of creating Machine Learning models to make predictions on values such as genres, the focus of this tutorial is to also present ideas on how to handle a Multiclass Classification problem, especially when there are significant imbalances in the classes. We hope this tutorial would shed some insight as to how the Machine Learning process works and would also provide more experienced Machine Learning enthusiasts with a different perspective on how to handle Multiclass Classification problems.

BPM¶

BPM stands for Beats Per Minute. It is a measure of how fast or slow paced the song is. Whether the data is sparse or dense, most genres have a good spread of BPM. Some genres like gangster rap will occupy the lower half of the spectrum, but those are outliers.

A lot of the heatmap makes sense:

  1. Acousticness has a poor correlation to Energy. While there could be many "Intense" and "Active" that are also produced using acoustic instruments such as Fiddle songs, a lot of those songs aren't popular anymore. Upbeat songs that are also popular would mostly be produced using electronic instruments.

  2. Valence has good correlation to Energy and Danceability. If a song "feels positive" there's a good chance there's a groove to dance to and the energy is high enough to dance to.

  3. Year has a good correlation to Loudness. Songs get louder as the years go by.

  4. Energy and Loudness have good correlation.

  5. Acousticness and Loudness have poor correlation. For the most part, unless the song is a loud orchestral piece, it's unlikely for an acoustic piece to be loud. For a song to be loud and still popular, it's likely that lots of audio engineering was involved, making it more likely to utilise electronic instruments.

  6. Weirdly, Popularity isn't a good indicator of a song's other features. It's highly likely popularity is affected by other external factors that aren't captured by the dataset, such as marketing, Spotify's own suggestions to it's users, and user demographic.

A Note on the Target Variable i.e. Top Genre¶

Looking at the count of the genres, we can that there is a major disparity in the representation of each genre. There are 149 unique genres in the dataset but there are only 10 genres that appear in the dataset more than 50 times, whereas there are up to 89 unique genres that appear in the dataset less than 5 times. Additionally, among the top 10 most appearing genres, there is a huge difference between the genre in first place and the genre in second place. These disparities in the appearance between the genres would result in major imbalances between the genres in the dataset and could ultimately affect the performances of the models that we would use to make our predictions.

Feature Engineering¶

Grouping the Genres¶

To handle the issue of imbalances, we chose to use a variety of methods with the first one being grouping identifiable sub-genres with their much more encompassing genres. An example of such a grouping would be grouping the Dutch Pop sub-genre with other sub-genres of pop to create a new genre that would be called Pop. This operation was done for only the genres of Rock, Pop, Folk, Hip Hop, and Metal as they were the only genres that we were able to easily identify their sub-genres. To do these groupings, we created a simple function that returned one of aforementioned genres if the sub-genre passed in as an argument contained the genre as part of its name. If the sub-genre passed in as an argument did not contain any of the genres as a substring of its name, then its original name was returned. To apply the function to the dataset, we first created a copy of the original data frame that we were previously working with and then used the apply function from pandas to create a new column called ‘New Genres’ from the result of calling the function on the ‘Top Genres’ column. Once this new column was created, we added it to the copy of the data frame that we created.

In [24]:
#print(df['Top Genre'].unique())
def group_genres(genre):
  if genre.find('rock') != -1:
    return 'Rock'
  elif genre.find('pop') != -1:
    return 'Pop'
  elif genre.find('folk') != -1:
    return 'Folk'
  elif genre.find('hip hop') != -1:
    return 'Hip Hop'
  elif genre.find('metal') != -1:
    return 'Metal'
  else:
    return genre

#df for grouped genres
df_copy1 = df.copy()
df_copy1['New Genres'] = df['Top Genre'].apply(group_genres)

One Hot Encoding the Artist Column¶

In addition to creating the ‘New Target’ column, which we eventually used as our target variable, we also added another much-needed feature to help with our model creation and predictions. Since we viewed the Artist name to be a crucial part of a song’s genre, we chose to make the ‘Artist’ feature a usable part for our models by one-hot encoding the column because the name of the artists was nominal data. To achieve this, we used the get_dummies function from Pandas and concatenated the result of the function to a copy of our original dataset and also to the dataset created in the previous step. Afterwards, we deleted the ‘Artist’ column as it was unneeded and proceeded to use the newly created copy of our data frame as our main data frame for the rest of the tutorial.

In [25]:

Initial Predictions with default parameters for each model¶

Prediction with Top Genre¶

At this stage of the tutorial, we will showcase how we went about creating our models and analyzing our models. The first choice we made was to use the default parameters for each of our chosen models and to train our models using the original dataset with the one hot encoded columns for the artist names. Before creating the models, we first split our data set into a training set and a test set by using the train_test_split function from Pandas. We chose to use a 60-40 split at this juncture as it is a very common choice used by most Machine Learning engineers. After creating our training data and test data, we then ventured into creating our models.

The first model we made was the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier. After fitting the model with out training data, we calculated the accuracy score because we aimed to utilize an extremely simplified approach at this stage of the tutorial. The accuracy of the model was poor to say the least with the model having an accuracy score of about 0.2. Although this was a really poor score, the other models did not fare much better than the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier, with the only exception being the Random Forest Classifier. Whereas the Logistic Regression model and the Decision Tree Classifier model had accuracy scores of about 0.2 and 0.3 respectively, the Random Forest Classifier model had an accuracy score of about 0.5 which was still relatively poor but a lot better than all the other models.

The poor scores of each of the models can be chalked up to a number of factors but the main factor that stands out is the imbalance between the genres in the dataset. This is especially apparent in the K-Nearest Neighbor Classifier which does not fare well with unbalanced classes, and the Logistic Regression model which already does not properly handle multiclass classification problems by default and proceeds to perform worse if the classes are imbalanced. These were the main issues that we attempted to address in the next steps and we attempted to do so in a variety of ways.

Prediction with New Genres¶

The next approach we took was training our models using the dataset that grouped sub-genres together to create new genres of their larger encompassing genres. The steps taken in this approach are exactly the same as the steps taken in the previous approach with the only exception being changing our training data and test data split. While we maintained the ratio of the split (60% training data – 40% test data), we had to change the contents of our target data as our new target variable is the ‘New Genres’ column and not the ‘Top Genres’ column.

After making these changes, we evaluated each model based on their accuracy score. The results showed a similar trend as the results in the last approach but we were able to experience a significant rise in the accuracy of each model.

Due to the change in the dataset, it can be inferred that the improvement in the accuracy scores of each model was a result of getting rid of some of the outliers in the dataset. This was especially evident in the Logistic Regression model as Logistic Regression models tend to perform better when the number of classes to classify are as small as possible.

Although this is an encouraging achievement, it still does not help us handle the issue of class imbalances as there are still genres that appear in the dataset less than 5 times and it can even be argued that grouping some of the sub genres together has led to greater class imbalances as pertains to the weights of the classes. To handle this issue, the next step we chose was to use some tools provided by scikitlearn and imbalanced-learn to adjust the weights of the classes. But before we did that, we first chose to perform a sort of sanity check.

Prediction With Cross Validation¶

Using Regular Genres¶

To ensure that our hypothesis has some truth to it, we chose to train our models using a different approach: Cross Validation. Cross Validation is a model training method that involves using random subsets of the dataset to train a model and evaluating the model’s performance on the other subsets not used in the training process. This method is used to detect and counter overfitting and could potentially counter other training issues as well.

To simplify this process, we used the cross_val_score function from sklearn which simultaneously performs cross validation on the given model and returns the model’s evaluation score. At this step of the tutorial, we chose to make the target variable the ‘Top Genre’ column. Although there are no major ideas to report at this stage, seeing as the models did not improve significantly if at all, we do see that the cross-validation procedure reflects the idea of an imbalance in our data. This is clear in the warning that states that ‘The least populated class in y has only 1 members, which is less than n_splits=10’ (currently hidden due to the filteration of the warnings in the notebook). This means that certain genres are not appropriately represented in our cross-validation splits which could ultimately affect our model’s performance and appears to do so as seen in the poor scores of each model.

Handling Class Imbalances¶

Using the Class Weight Paramater¶

The second approach we took to handle the class imbalances was by using the class_weight parameter that is a part of the Logistic Regression, Decision Tree Classifier, and Random Forest Classifier models. This parameter determines how to weight each class in the target variable so as to handle class imbalances in the dataset. Since our aim was to make each of the classes balanced, we chose to set the class_weight parameter to be ‘balanced’ so that each genre can be weighted similarly. The formula the weight of each genre given this setting is no_of_samples / (no_of_classes * np.bincount(y)). The purpose of this formula is to make classes with a lot samples be less weighted and to increase the weight the significantly less weighted classes. While this parameter was available to us to use for the Logistic Regression, Decision Tree Classifier, and Random Forest Classifier models, it was not available to us for the K-Nearest Neighbors model, which was disappointing to say the least but we proceeded nonetheless.

To train our models, we used the ‘Top Genre’ column as our target variable and made our predictions on that column. While we were optimistic about our decision to use the class weight parameter, things did not turn out the way we expected them to with the major disappointment being the significant drop in the accuracy of our Logistic Regression model as the model had an underwhelming accuracy score and f1 score.

While the Decision Tree and Random Forest models fared better than the Logistic Regression model, they did not have significantly good scores either. To aim to improve these scores, we chose a different route to counter imbalances, and to do that we had to use a class called SMOTE.

Side Note: The f1 score metric uses a weighted average since we are performing multiclass classification and there are some imbalances between the classes.

Using SMOTE and Pipeline to handle Imbalances¶

SMOTE is a class provided by the imbalanced-learn module that helps to counter imbalanced classes in classification problems. To give a brief overview about what SMOTE does without going into too much detail, SMOTE balances the class distribution by randomly increasing minority class examples by replicating them. It then uses these new synthetic training records to reconstruct the dataset to have a better distribution of the classes to be classified. In addition to using SMOTE, we also used the Pipeline class which is a preprocessing tool for models and the Standard Scaler class which we used to standardize our dataset.

Now that the tools that we used have been explained it is time to explain our process. We firstly removed the major outliers in our ‘Top Genre’ column, ie genres with appearances less than 15, because although SMOTE creates synthetic examples for minority classes, significantly minor classes have such limited information that SMOTE would be unable to synthesize examples for them. After doing that, we created our training data and test data using the train_test_split function. Next, we created each model. To create the models, we used the make_pipeline function and used SMOTE, StandardScaler, and the specific model that were interested in as the parameters of the function. So the better illustrate this, to create the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier model, we made the following function call: make_pipeline(SMOTE(random_state=42), StandardScaler(), KNeighborsClassifier()). This process was replicated for the other models and we evaluated the models using the accuracy score and the f1 score since we wanted to take into account the varying classes.

As a result of using this approach, we experienced massive improvements especially in the The K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier and the Logistic Regression model. Unfortunately, the same could not be said for the Decision Tree Classifier and the Random Forest Classifier which did not fare as expected following our approach. To mitigate this, we chose to train our models using the same dataframe without the outlier data but we opted not to use Pipeline and SMOTE in our training process. This resulted in the Decision Tree Classifier and the Random Forest Classifier experiencing major improvements to their accuracy and f1 scores.

Now that we had what we deemed to be our best models, we proceeded to tune the hyperparameters of each model.

Hyperparameter Tuning for Each Model¶

To tune the hyperparameters for each model, we chose to use different approaches for the different models. For the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier and the Logistic Regression model, we had to manually adjust the hyperparameters ourselves since we created the models using the make_pipeline function whereas for the Decision Tree Classifier and the Random Forest Classifier, we used GridSearchCV since we opted to use the models that were not trained using the make_pipeline function.

For the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier and the Logistic Regression model, the hyperparameters that we chose to adjust were the n-neighbors parameter and C parameter respectively. We chose these parameters because we did not want to overcomplicate the process and because we wanted to limit the number of computational resources expended to train the models. Once we came up with a list of the values to evaluate the models on, we used a for loop to test the impact of using each value and chose the best value based on the f1 score metric.

For the Decision Tree Classifier and the Random Forest Classifier, we chose to use GridSearchCV to tune their hyperparameters. For the Decision Tree, we chose to tune the splitter, max_depth, and criterion parameters and for the Random Forest Classifier, we chose to tune the n_estimators, max_depth, and criterion parameters.

Following the tuning process, we found our best models to be the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier, the Logistic Regression model , and the Random Forest Classifier.

While these were good scores for each of the models, we first had to ensure that the models are genuinely producing these results before we could conclude on our accuracy and to do that, we opted to use hypothesis testing.

#list of possible values for n-neighbors
k_range = list(range(10, 310, 10))
k_range.insert(0, 5)

#variables to keep track of the features of the best knn model
knn_best_model = knn_pipeline
knn_best_prediction = knn_pipeline_prediction
knn_best_acc = accuracy_score(y_test_smote, knn_best_prediction)
knn_best_f1_score = f1_score(y_test_smote, knn_best_prediction, average='weighted')
k_value = 0

#creating a model with each value of k
for neighbor in k_range:
  current_model = make_pipeline(SMOTE(random_state=42), StandardScaler(), KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=neighbor))
  current_model = current_model.fit(X_train_smote, y_train_smote)
  current_model_prediction = current_model.predict(X_test_smote)
  current_model_acc = accuracy_score(y_test_smote, current_model_prediction)
  current_model_f1_score = f1_score(y_test_smote, current_model_prediction, average='weighted')

  if current_model_f1_score >= knn_best_f1_score:
    knn_best_model = current_model
    knn_best_prediction = current_model_prediction
    knn_best_acc = current_model_acc
    knn_best_f1_score = current_model_f1_score
    k_value = neighbor

#outputting the features of the best model
print('KNN Best Model Accuracy:', knn_best_acc)
print('KNN Best Model F1 Score:', knn_best_f1_score)
print('K Value:', k_value)
print(classification_report(y_test_smote, knn_best_prediction))

c_value = 1

#creating a model with each value of k
for c in c_values:
  current_model = make_pipeline(SMOTE(random_state=42), StandardScaler(), LogisticRegression(C=c))
  current_model = current_model.fit(X_train_smote, y_train_smote)
  current_model_prediction = current_model.predict(X_test_smote)
  current_model_acc = accuracy_score(y_test_smote, current_model_prediction)
  current_model_f1_score = f1_score(y_test_smote, current_model_prediction, average='weighted')

  if current_model_f1_score >= log_reg_best_f1_score:
    log_reg_best_model = current_model
    log_reg_best_prediction = current_model_prediction
    log_reg_best_acc = current_model_acc
    log_reg_best_f1_score = current_model_f1_score
    c_value = c

#outputting the features of the best model
print('Logistic Regression Best Model Accuracy:', log_reg_best_acc)
print('Logistic Regression Best Model F1 Score:', log_reg_best_f1_score)
print('C Value:', k_value)
print(classification_report(y_test_smote, log_reg_best_prediction))

Hypothesis Testing¶

The Hypothesis Testing approach we used was done using the chi2_contigency function, which performs a Chi-squared test, from the scipy.stats module. Our null hypothesis for each model was that the model being tested was not a random guesser and we set our confidence interval to be 99%. This value for the confidence interval was chosen to account for Type 1 and Type 2 errors.

Following our results, we found that all the chosen models were not random guessers and we were unable to reject the null hypothesis.

1. K-Nearest Neighbors¶

In [94]:
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test_smote, knn_best_prediction)
stat, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(conf_matrix)
print('Chi-square statistic=',stat)
print('P Value=',p)
alpha=0.01
if p < alpha:
    print('Model is not a random guesser')
else:
    print('Model is a random guesser')

Conclusion and Future Considerations¶

In this tutorial we presented our approach to solving a multiclass classification problem by attempting to predict the genre of a song based on various features of the song. While this initially started off as a straightforward problem, we eventually had to deal with the imbalances between each genre in the dataset. To handle this issue, we settled on removing outliers from the dataset and using the SMOTE class to balance out each genre in the dataset.

While we have positive results from our findings, we think there are still methods we would have to utilize in the future to improve our models' accuracies such as creating more features for each genre or using only specific features for each genre, but this has definitely been a good start.
